Node.Notes: Some change word slightly to yield "happy/blessed." Tree assumes relative phrase forms an np. Either way, the general sense is that the wicked think they will not be in trouble throughout all generations.
Translation of this verse is uncertain, which many different proposals, though most agree that general sense is that the hapless (continuing from v. 9) are defeated.
Tree assumes "the intimidated/disheartened army [referring to the hapless] fall under his mighty ones [referring to the multitudes/the might/maybe claws [of a lion] of the wicked]."
Uncertain if in a positive sense of taking in your hand to help/deliver or in a negative sense of taking vengeance.
(SYNTAX) Similar to dislocated np, but no pronoun referring back to it; so chose to represent as ADV.
